I was looking for a comprehensive course on GitHub actions and I found this. Here, the instructor covers all the details of the GitHub actions workflow including how to use GitHub to build apps, how to deploy those apps, how to use CD to deploy apps to multiple environments and how to deploy apps to a Kubernetes cluster. This course is a great resource for anyone who wants to learn more about project deployment and wants to reduce or eliminate manual deployment tasks. The course is full of examples, clear explanations and is presented in a fun and easy to understand manner.

As a developer, it's important to understand the tools we use. By knowing how something works we can make better decisions about when, where and how to use it. In this case, the tool is GitHub Actions, a CI/CD service on GitHub.

If you're looking to understand how to setup your infra environment and deploy your app, this course is great. Very well organized, with an intuitive build and deployment processes. I have learned how to use the CD workflow in depth and make the most of the new features of the CD workflow. I have also learned how to create and use my own CD workflow.
he course is very compact and to the point. Short and very effective.

I'm already a fan of the CI CD with GitHub Actions Workflow, because I can see how to design a deployment process with GitHub Actions and how it works with the CD workflow.

This on-line course in fourteen sections includes worksheets and truly covers all the fundamentals of creating stories from award winning, multi-published fantasy author Hank Quense.  

A step-by-step approach to writing a story using slides and lectures includes looking at the elements of plot from the main conflict, creation of  characters, the setting, the point of view, the sequence of events, the use of subplots, the climax, and the resolution. “You need many ideas for writing a story” according to Hank Quense who also feels that this process takes time and hard work. 

The tutorial reminds writers to consider who they are writing for -- their readers - every step of the way. To draw the reader in, make them care about the story, you must make the characters seem real and identify the emotions you want the reader to experience through those characters. 
Taking brief examples from Star Wars, Lord of the Rings, and The Hangover, as well as Hank Quense’s own books, provides insight into how it can be done.

For those of us who'd rather be writing than learning about writing but keep hitting roadblocks, this is a marvelously compact guide to better writing. In 14 short sessions, Hank Quense covers the whole challenge - from basic idea to setting and characters and plot and voice. The advice applies to everything from novel to short story to memoir. His language is as blunt and devoid of wasted verbiage as he urges us to be. To drive home his advice, each section comes with exercises, listed under the "resource" button. We can put in as much or as little effort as we choose, but if we do the  "homework" I reckon it's guaranteed to give us a much stronger foundation, and a pretty exciting start to our books.

- At times the voice-over lags behind what the instructor is doing on screen. For instance, when the instructor is going through quick motions in the Unity Editor, it can be challenging at times when adding new game objects to the scene and insuring the right components are attached before running.
- As one of the main features of this class was to run test cases. For future reference for those who are taking this course, I suggest you watch Section 6 LAST. An example would be Section 7's implementation of the user interface and the available stat points for leveling up primary stats. This is such a comprehensive course that i don't even know where to start the review. I want to start saying that the way Alfred teaches is clear and straight to the point.
Half of the course is about making UI visually using Godot, understanding how Godot works and how Godot deals with user interface elements (nodes).
The other half has a lot of coding - but the course never tells you to "just copy me", instead, Alfred explains EVERYTHING, to the point of drawing diagrams and connections between each line of code. THIS IS HOW coding should be taught everywhere. 
To my surprise, initially I thought the course description was a bit over the top - because it promises a lot of things, but it's actually accurate! I started knowing nothing about Godot and I learned a lot from scratch with the course.
This course is not about making game mechanics (and it never promises that). it's a course about game ui development, Godot, GDScript, dynamic game systems and data architecture. I don't think there's any course like this out there.
Notice that I'm a software developer by day so my opinion is based with my knowledge of programming multiple programming languages, I don't know how the course would be for a complete beginner in the subject. The course never felt too boring neither too hard - there was a video here and there that was too fast, but overall the pacing is ok.
I really enjoy the content and the way the instructor is presenting the information.
